# Physical Structures

### Basic Idea

**Physical structure refers to how devices are physically connected in a network.**

It describes the **actual layout of network devices and cables**.

Physical structures mainly include:

1️⃣ **Type of Connection**
2️⃣ **Physical Topology**

---

# PART 1: Type of Connection

There are **two types of connections between devices**.

### 1️⃣ Point-to-Point Connection

### Definition

A **point-to-point connection** connects **two devices directly using a dedicated link**.

```text
Device A  ─────────  Device B
```

Only these **two devices share the link**.

### Examples

* Telephone connection
* Direct cable between two computers
* Router-to-router connection

### Key Characteristics

* Dedicated link
* High speed
* Secure communication

---

### 2️⃣ Multipoint Connection

### Definition

A **multipoint connection** connects **multiple devices using a single shared link**.

```text
Device A
     │
Device B ───── Shared Link
     │
Device C
```

All devices **share the same communication channel**.

### Examples

* WiFi network
* Bus topology networks
* Shared Ethernet networks

### Key Characteristics

* Shared medium
* Lower cost
* Bandwidth shared among devices

---

# PART 2: Physical Topology

**Network topology describes the physical arrangement of devices in a network.**

Your notes list **four major topologies**. 

1️⃣ Mesh
2️⃣ Star
3️⃣ Bus
4️⃣ Ring

---

# 1️⃣ Mesh Topology

### Definition

In **mesh topology**, every device is connected to **every other device**.

```text
A ─── B
│ ╲  │
│  ╲ │
C ─── D
```

Each connection is **point-to-point**.

### Formula

Number of links required:

[
n(n-1)/2
]

where **n = number of devices**

### Advantages

✔ Very reliable
✔ No traffic congestion
✔ High security

### Disadvantages

❌ Expensive
❌ Complex installation
❌ Requires many cables

---

# 2️⃣ Star Topology

### Definition

In **star topology**, all devices connect to a **central device**.

Central device can be:

* Switch
* Hub
* Router

```text
        A
        │
B ── Switch ── C
        │
        D
```

### Advantages

✔ Easy to install
✔ Easy to manage
✔ Failure of one device doesn't affect others

### Disadvantages

❌ Central device failure stops network
❌ More cable required

---

# 3️⃣ Bus Topology

### Definition

In **bus topology**, all devices share a **single backbone cable**.

```text
A ── B ── C ── D ── E
      │ Backbone Cable │
```

### Advantages

✔ Low cost
✔ Simple design

### Disadvantages

❌ Backbone failure stops entire network
❌ Difficult to troubleshoot
❌ Performance decreases with more devices

---

# 4️⃣ Ring Topology

### Definition

In **ring topology**, devices are connected in a **circular loop**.

```text
A ── B
│    │
D ── C
```

Data travels **around the ring**.

### Advantages

✔ Organized communication
✔ No collision

### Disadvantages

❌ One device failure can stop the network
❌ Difficult to add new devices

---

# 📊 Topology Comparison

| Topology | Structure              | Main Feature        |
| -------- | ---------------------- | ------------------- |
| Mesh     | Every device connected | High reliability    |
| Star     | Central hub/switch     | Easy management     |
| Bus      | Single backbone cable  | Low cost            |
| Ring     | Circular connection    | Organized data flow |

---

**Physical Structures**

Physical structure refers to the physical layout of devices and communication links in a network.

It includes:

**1. Type of Connection**

* Point-to-Point
* Multipoint

**2. Physical Topology**

* Mesh
* Star
* Bus
* Ring

Each topology defines how devices are connected and how data flows within the network.

